        "content": "<p>These <code>Fintype</code> instances are a little subtle, especially if you think as a mathematician. Giving a <code>Fintype</code> instance is <em>not</em> the same as saying that something is <code>Finite</code>, it more or less means to fix an ordering (and that the thing is finite). In particular you can have two incompatible <code>Fintype</code> instances, and this is what was happening here.</p>",
        "id": 542307954,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1759246407
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You may ask: which two?<br>\nWell, the point is that <code>path_system G A B</code> is an <code>abbrev</code> for  <code>(σ : Equiv.Perm (Fin n)) × ((i : Fin n) → G.Walk (A i) (B (σ i)))</code>, and Lean sees through <code>abbrev</code>. In particular, when it needs a <code>Fintype</code> instance for <code>path_system G A B</code> it looks if it has one for <code>(σ : Equiv.Perm (Fin n)) × ((i : Fin n) → G.Walk (A i) (B (σ i)))</code>: now, this is a product, so Lean knows that it is enough to find one for each factor. It keeps reasoning like that and at end it is able to produce, automatically, a <code>Fintype</code> instance on <code>path_system G A B</code>.</p>\n<p>Now, the line <code>noncomputable instance : Fintype (path_system G A B) := Fintype.ofFinite _</code> means: chose a totally random <code>Fintype</code> instance, one nobody can say anything about.</p>",
        "id": 542308824,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1759246630
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>At the end you have fixed two ordering on your type, and so there are two ways of computing the sum (of course the result is the same, but this is not totally transparent to Lean), so the system complains.</p>",
        "id": 542309116,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1759246703
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"130384\">@Riccardo Brasca</span> , oh, thank you for so much! This is a really detailed and enlightening explanation.</p>",
        "id": 542309973,
        "sender_full_name": "Egor Morozov",
        "timestamp": 1759246899
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In general don't add any instance unless Lean complains that it is not able to find one.</p>",
        "id": 542310429,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1759247017
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see, that is exactly my mistake here. I was sure I need <code>Fintype</code>instance to write the sum but it turned out that Lean was able to synthesize it.</p>",
        "id": 542332911,
        "sender_full_name": "Egor Morozov",
        "timestamp": 1759253769
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We tried to make system working as you would do on paper:you have to assume that something is finite in your work, but then all other finiteness condition are automatic, and you should to be worried about them.</p>",
